ler’s philosophy of gender difference. Why should one try to connect these strains of thinking? What might make the work of these thinkers negotiable with one another? This volume finds that bridge in an emphasis on “becoming” that secretly defines the philosophies of Whitehead, Deleuze, and Butler. Its three sections investigate their surprising confluence in a “philosophy of becoming” in relation to the question of the event, bodies and societies, and immanence and divinity. A substantial Introduction gives an extended comparison of the three thinkers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBell, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaber, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaber, Roland, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGudmarsdottir, Sigridur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalewood, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiggins, Luke B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeller, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalin, Isabella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaviro, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStephenson, Andrea M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStephenson, Andrea M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVan Wyk, Alan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070